    <item>
      <title>Basis</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/basis/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/basis/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A basis of a &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector space&lt;/a&gt; is a collection of &lt;a href=&#34;./vector.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vectors&lt;/a&gt; that are, in a precise sense, both sufficient and minimal: sufficient to build every vector in the space, and minimal in that none of them is redundant. A basis gives a coordinate system — once you choose a basis, every vector can be described uniquely by a list of numbers (its coordinates with respect to that basis).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formally, a set of vectors &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;…&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_n\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in a vector space &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;V&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a basis if it satisfies two conditions. First, the set spans &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;V&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: every vector in &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;V&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; can be expressed as a linear combination &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a_1 v_1 + a_2 v_2 + \cdots + a_n v_n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for some scalars &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;…&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a_1, \ldots, a_n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; from the underlying &lt;a href=&#34;../../algebra/terms/field.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;field&lt;/a&gt;. Second, the set is linearly independent: the only way to produce the zero vector as a linear combination is with all coefficients zero (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a_1 v_1 + \cdots + a_n v_n = \mathbf{0}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; implies &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋯&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a_1 = \cdots = a_n = 0&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;). These two conditions together guarantee that the representation of each vector as a linear combination is unique — spanning ensures existence, independence ensures uniqueness.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Determinant</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/determinant/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/determinant/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The determinant is a single number you can compute from a square &lt;a href=&#34;./matrix.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;matrix&lt;/a&gt; that tells you something fundamental about the &lt;a href=&#34;./linear-map.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;linear map&lt;/a&gt; the matrix represents: whether it collapses space, and if not, by how much it scales volumes and whether it flips orientation.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For a &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;2 \times 2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; matrix, the formula is simple: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;det&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⁡&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtable rowspacing=&#34;0.16em&#34; columnalign=&#34;center center&#34; columnspacing=&#34;1em&#34;&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;/mtable&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;d&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\det \begin{pmatrix} a &amp;amp; b \\ c &amp;amp; d \end{pmatrix} = ad - bc&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Consider the matrix &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtable rowspacing=&#34;0.16em&#34; columnalign=&#34;center center&#34; columnspacing=&#34;1em&#34;&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;/mtable&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\begin{pmatrix} 3 &amp;amp; 0 \\ 0 &amp;amp; 2 \end{pmatrix}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, which stretches the &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;-axis by 3 and the &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;-axis by 2. Its determinant is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;3 \cdot 2 - 0 \cdot 0 = 6&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — exactly the factor by which it scales areas. A unit square becomes a &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;3 \times 2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; rectangle with area 6. Now consider &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtable rowspacing=&#34;0.16em&#34; columnalign=&#34;center center&#34; columnspacing=&#34;1em&#34;&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;/mtable&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\begin{pmatrix} 0 &amp;amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp;amp; 0 \end{pmatrix}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, which swaps the two axes (a reflection). Its determinant is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;0 \cdot 0 - 1 \cdot 1 = -1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: the area is preserved (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∣&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∣&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;|{-1}| = 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) but orientation is reversed (the sign is negative).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Dimension</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/dimension/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/dimension/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The dimension of a &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector space&lt;/a&gt; is the number of &lt;a href=&#34;./vector.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vectors&lt;/a&gt; in any &lt;a href=&#34;./basis.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;basis&lt;/a&gt; — the number of independent directions in the space. The real line &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;double-struck&#34;&gt;R&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbb{R}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is one-dimensional: a single number determines a point. The plane &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;double-struck&#34;&gt;R&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbb{R}^2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is two-dimensional: you need two numbers (an &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;-coordinate and a &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;-coordinate). Ordinary space &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;double-struck&#34;&gt;R&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbb{R}^3&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is three-dimensional: three numbers are needed. The pattern extends: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;double-struck&#34;&gt;R&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbb{R}^n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; has dimension &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, meaning &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; independent numbers are needed to specify a point.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Dimension is well-defined because all bases of a given vector space have the same cardinality. This is a nontrivial theorem, not an obvious fact. A priori, you might worry that one basis could have 3 vectors and another could have 4. But this cannot happen: any two bases of the same space are in bijection. (In the finite-dimensional case, this is proved by the Steinitz exchange lemma; the infinite-dimensional case requires the axiom of choice.) Because the basis size is invariant, dimension is an intrinsic property of the space — it does not depend on which basis you happen to choose.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Eigenvalue</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/eigenvalue/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/eigenvalue/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Most &lt;a href=&#34;./linear-map.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;linear maps&lt;/a&gt; scramble directions — they stretch space one way, compress it another, and rotate things sideways. But along certain special directions, a linear map does something simple: it just scales. An eigenvalue is the scaling factor along one of these special directions, and the direction itself is called an eigenvector.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formally, if &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T: V \to V&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a linear map on a &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector space&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;V&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, then a scalar &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is an eigenvalue of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; if there exists a nonzero &lt;a href=&#34;./vector.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{v}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; such that &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T(\mathbf{v}) = \lambda \mathbf{v}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The vector &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{v}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is an eigenvector corresponding to &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The equation says that &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; acts on &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{v}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; by pure scaling — it sends &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;v&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{v}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; to &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; times itself, without changing its direction. When &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda &amp;gt; 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, the map stretches along that direction. When &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;0 &amp;lt; \lambda &amp;lt; 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, it compresses. When &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda &amp;lt; 0&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, it reverses direction (and scales). When &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;0&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda = 0&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, the map collapses that direction entirely.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Linear Map</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/linear-map/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/linear-map/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A linear map is a function between &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector spaces&lt;/a&gt; that respects the vector space structure — it preserves both addition and scalar multiplication. If you add two vectors and then apply the map, you get the same result as applying the map to each vector separately and then adding. If you scale a vector and then apply the map, you get the same result as applying the map first and then scaling.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Matrix</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/matrix/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/matrix/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A matrix is a rectangular grid of numbers (or more generally, elements of a &lt;a href=&#34;../../algebra/terms/field.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;field&lt;/a&gt;), arranged in rows and columns. An &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;m \times n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; matrix has &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;m&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;m&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; rows and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; columns. You write the entry in the &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;i&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;th row and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;j&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;j&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;th column as &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;j&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a_{ij}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. A &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;×&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;2 \times 3&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; matrix looks like &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mtable rowspacing=&#34;0.16em&#34; columnalign=&#34;center center center&#34; columnspacing=&#34;1em&#34;&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;3&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;mtr&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;4&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;5&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;mtd&gt;&lt;mstyle scriptlevel=&#34;0&#34; displaystyle=&#34;false&#34;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;6&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mstyle&gt;&lt;/mtd&gt;&lt;/mtr&gt;&lt;/mtable&gt;&lt;mo fence=&#34;true&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp;amp; 2 &amp;amp; 3 \\ 4 &amp;amp; 5 &amp;amp; 6 \end{pmatrix}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — two rows, three columns, six entries.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Matrices are useful because they represent &lt;a href=&#34;./linear-map.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;linear maps&lt;/a&gt;. Once you choose a &lt;a href=&#34;./basis.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;basis&lt;/a&gt; for each &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector space&lt;/a&gt; involved, any linear map &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;V&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;W&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T: V \to W&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; between finite-dimensional spaces can be written as a matrix — the columns of the matrix are the images of the basis vectors, expressed in coordinates. This representation converts the abstract question &amp;ldquo;what does this linear map do?&amp;rdquo; into the concrete question &amp;ldquo;what numbers are in this grid?&amp;rdquo; Applying the map to a vector becomes multiplying the matrix by a column of numbers.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Vector</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/vector/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/vector/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A vector is an element of a &lt;a href=&#34;./vector-space.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vector space&lt;/a&gt; — anything that can be added to others of its kind and scaled by numbers from a &lt;a href=&#34;../../algebra/terms/field.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;field&lt;/a&gt;. The word brings to mind arrows in space: a direction and a magnitude, drawn as a line segment with a pointed tip. That image is useful but narrow. Arrows in two- or three-dimensional space are vectors, but so are columns of numbers, polynomials, continuous functions, and sequences of real numbers. What makes something a vector is not what it looks like, but what you can do with it.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Vector Space</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/vector-space/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/linear-algebra/terms/vector-space/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A vector space is a collection of objects — called &lt;a href=&#34;./vector.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;vectors&lt;/a&gt; — that can be added together and scaled by numbers from a &lt;a href=&#34;../../algebra/terms/field.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;field&lt;/a&gt;, in a way that behaves the way addition and scaling ought to behave. The field supplies the scalars: these might be the real numbers, the complex numbers, or any other field. The vectors themselves might be arrows in space, columns of numbers, functions, polynomials, or any of a hundred other things. What makes them a vector space is not what they are, but how they combine.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
